# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crypto-wallets
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Bitcoin works through the collaboration of computers, each of which acts as a node in the peer-to-peer bitcoin network.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Each node maintains an independent copy of a public distributed ledger of transactions, called a blockchain, without central oversight.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Transactions are validated through the use of cryptography, preventing one person from spending another person's bitcoin, as long as the owner of the bitcoin keeps certain sensitive data secret.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Consensus between nodes about the content of the blockchain is achieved using a computationally intensive process based on proof of work, called mining, which is performed by purpose-built computers.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Mining consumes large quantities of electricity, with surveyed miners reporting that 52% of their electricity use came from sustainable energy sources, and has been criticized for its environmental impact.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Before bitcoin, several digital cash technologies were released, starting with David Chaum's ecash in the 1980s.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The idea that solutions to computational puzzles could have some value was first proposed by cryptographers Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor in 1992.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The concept was independently rediscovered by Adam Back who developed Hashcash, a proof-of-work scheme for spam control in 1997.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The first proposals for distributed digital scarcity-based cryptocurrencies came from cypherpunks Wei Dai (b-money) and Nick Szabo (bit gold) in 1998.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In 2004, Hal Finney developed the first currency based on reusable proof of work.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] These various attempts were not successful: Chaum's concept required centralized control and no banks wanted to sign on, Hashcash had no protection against double-spending, while b-money and bit gold were not resistant to Sybil attacks.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The domain name *bitcoin.org* was registered on 18 August 2008.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] On 31 October 2008, a link to a white paper authored by Satoshi Nakamoto titled *Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System* was posted to a cryptography mailing list.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] According to computer scientist Arvind Narayanan, all individual components of bitcoin originated in earlier academic literature.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Nakamoto's innovation was their complex interplay which resulted in the first decentralized, Sybil resistant, Byzantine fault tolerant digital cash system, that would eventually be referred to as the first blockchain.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Nakamoto's paper was not peer-reviewed and was initially ignored by academics, who argued that it could not work.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Nakamoto released bitcoin as open-source software.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] On 3 January 2009, the bitcoin network was created when Nakamoto mined the starting block of the chain, known as the *genesis block*.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Embedded in this block was the text "The Times 03/Jan/2009 Chancellor on brink of second bailout for banks", which is the date and headline of an issue of *The Times* newspaper.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Nine days later, Hal Finney received the first bitcoin transaction: ten bitcoins from Nakamoto.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Wei Dai and Nick Szabo were also early supporters.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] On May 22, 2010, the first known commercial transaction using bitcoin occurred when programmer Laszlo Hanyecz bought two Papa John's pizzas for ₿10,000, in what would later be celebrated as "Bitcoin Pizza Day".
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Satoshi tasked Finnish developer and early Bitcoin contributor Martti Malmi with creating content for the bitcoin.org website.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Blockchain analysts estimate that Nakamoto had mined about one million bitcoins before he disappeared in 2010 and handed the network alert key and control of the code repository over to Gavin Andresen.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Andresen later became lead developer at the Bitcoin Foundation, an organization founded in September 2012 to promote bitcoin.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] After early "proof-of-concept" transactions, the first major users of bitcoin were black markets, such as the dark web Silk Road.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] During its 30 months of existence, beginning in February 2011, Silk Road exclusively accepted bitcoins as payment, transacting ₿9.9 million, worth about $214 million.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In May 2013, US authorities seized the unregistered exchange Mt.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In June 2013, the US Drug Enforcement Administration seized ₿11.02 from an individual attempting to use them to purchase illicit drugs.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] This marked the first time a government agency had seized bitcoins.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The FBI seized about ₿30,000 in October 2013 from Silk Road, following the arrest of its founder Ross Ulbricht.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In December 2013, the People's Bank of China prohibited Chinese financial institutions from using bitcoin.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] After the announcement, the value of bitcoin dropped, and Baidu no longer accepted bitcoins for certain services.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Buying real-world goods with any virtual currency had been illegal in China since at least 2009.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Research produced by the University of Cambridge estimated that in 2017, there were 2.9 to 5.8 million unique users using a cryptocurrency wallet, most of them using bitcoin.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In August 2017, the SegWit software upgrade was activated.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Segwit was intended to support the Lightning Network as well as improve scalability.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] SegWit opponents, who supported larger blocks as a scalability solution, forked to create Bitcoin Cash, one of many forks of bitcoin.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In December 2017, the first futures on bitcoin was introduced by the Chicago Mercantile Exchange (CME).
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In February 2018, the price crashed after China imposed a complete ban on bitcoin trading.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The percentage of bitcoin trading in the Chinese renminbi fell from over 90% in September 2017 to less than 1% in June 2018.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] During the same year, bitcoin prices were negatively affected by several hacks or thefts from cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In 2020, some major companies and institutions started to acquire bitcoin: MicroStrategy invested $250 million in bitcoin as a treasury reserve asset, Square, Inc., $50 million, and MassMutual, $100 million.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In November 2020, PayPal added support for bitcoin in the US.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In February 2021, bitcoin's market capitalization reached $1 trillion for the first time.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In November 2021, the Taproot soft-fork upgrade was activated, adding support for Schnorr signatures, improved functionality of smart contracts and Lightning Network.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Before, bitcoin only used a custom elliptic curve with the ECDSA algorithm to produce signatures.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In September 2021, bitcoin became legal tender currency in El Salvador, alongside the US dollar.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In October 2021, the first bitcoin futures exchange-traded fund (ETF), called BITO, from ProShares was approved by the SEC and listed on the CME.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In early 2022, during the Canadian trucker protests opposing COVID-19 vaccine mandates, organizers turned to bitcoin to receive donations after traditional financial platforms restricted access to funding.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Proponents highlighted bitcoin's use as a tool for fundraising in situations where access to conventional financial systems may be restricted.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In May and June 2022, the bitcoin price fell following the collapses of TerraUSD, a stablecoin, and the Celsius Network, a cryptocurrency loan company.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In 2023, ordinals—non-fungible tokens (NFTs)—on bitcoin, went live.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] As of June 2023, River Financial estimated that bitcoin had 81.7 million users, about 1% of the global population.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In January 2024, the first 11 US spot bitcoin ETFs began trading, offering direct exposure to bitcoin for the first time on American stock exchanges.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In December 2024, bitcoin price reached $100,000 for the first time, as US president-elect Donald Trump promised to make the US the "crypto capital of the planet" and to stockpile bitcoin.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The same month, BlackRock, the world's largest asset manager, recommended investors to allocate up to 2% of their portfolio to bitcoin.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] As of 2025, the Salvadoran government continues to describe Bitcoin as legal tender under the 2021 Bitcoin Law; however, a January 2025 reform removed obligations for businesses and the government to accept it, so many analysts regard its legal-tender status as effectively ended in practice.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In March 2025, President Trump signed an executive order to establish a strategic bitcoin reserve.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Later that year, some U.S. states, such as Texas and New Hampshire also instituted strategic bitcoin reserves, and the Czech National Bank bought less than €1 million in a "test portfolio".
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Bitcoin logos made by Satoshi Nakamoto in 2009 (left) and 2010 (right).
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The unit of account of the bitcoin system is the *bitcoin*.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] It is most commonly represented with the symbol ₿ designed in 2010 and the currency code BTC.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] However, the BTC code does not conform to ISO 4217 as BT is the country code of Bhutan, and ISO 4217 requires the first letter used in global commodities to be 'X'.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] XBT, a code that conforms to ISO 4217 though not officially part of it, is used by Bloomberg L.P.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] No uniform capitalization convention exists; some sources use *Bitcoin*, capitalized, to refer to the technology and network, and *bitcoin*, lowercase, for the unit of account.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The *Cambridge Advanced Learner's Dictionary* and the *Oxford Advanced Learner's Dictionary* use the capitalized and lowercase variants without distinction.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] One bitcoin is divisible to eight decimal places.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Units for smaller amounts of bitcoin are the millibitcoin (mBTC), equal to 1⁄1000 bitcoin, and the satoshi (sat), representing 1⁄100000000 (one hundred millionth) bitcoin, the smallest amount possible.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] As a decentralized system, bitcoin operates without a central authority or single administrator, so that anyone can create a new bitcoin address and transact without needing any approval.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] This is accomplished through a specialized distributed ledger called a *blockchain* that records bitcoin transactions.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The blockchain is implemented as an ordered list of *blocks*.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Each block contains a SHA-256 hash of the previous block, chaining them in chronological order.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The blockchain is maintained by a peer-to-peer network.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Individual blocks, public addresses, and transactions within blocks are public information, and can be examined using a blockchain explorer.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Nodes validate and broadcast transactions.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Each node maintains a copy of the blockchain for ownership verification.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] A new block is created every 10 minutes on average, updating the blockchain across all nodes without central oversight.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] This process tracks bitcoin spending, ensuring each bitcoin is spent only once.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Unlike a traditional ledger that tracks physical currency, bitcoins exist digitally as unspent outputs of transactions.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In the blockchain, bitcoins are linked to specific strings called addresses.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Most often, an address encodes a hash of a single public key.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Creating such an address involves generating a random private key and then computing the corresponding address.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] This process is almost instant, but the reverse (finding the private key for a given address) is nearly impossible.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Publishing such a bitcoin address does not risk its private key, and it is extremely unlikely to accidentally generate a used key with funds.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] To use bitcoins, owners need their private key to digitally sign transactions, which are verified by the network using the public key, keeping the private key secret.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] An address may encode the hash of a bitcoin script that specifies more complex requirements to spend the funds.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] One common example is "multisig", in which multiple distinct private keys must mutually sign any transaction that attempts to spend the funds.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Bitcoin transactions use a Forth-like scripting language, involving one or more inputs and outputs.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] When sending bitcoins, a user specifies the recipients' addresses and the amount for each output.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] This allows sending bitcoins to several recipients in a single transaction.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] To prevent double-spending, each input must refer to a previous unspent output in the blockchain.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Using multiple inputs is similar to using multiple coins in a cash transaction.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] As in a cash transaction, the sum of inputs can exceed the intended sum of payments.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In such a case, an additional output can return the change back to the payer.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Unallocated input satoshis in the transaction become the transaction fee.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Losing a private key means losing access to the bitcoins, with no other proof of ownership accepted by the protocol.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] For instance, in 2013, a user lost ₿7,500, valued at US$7.5 million, by accidentally discarding a hard drive with the private key.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] It is estimated that around 20% of all bitcoins are lost.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The private key must also be kept secret as its exposure, such as through a data breach, can lead to theft of the associated bitcoins.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] As of December 2017, approximately ₿980,000 had been stolen from cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Miners don't directly act as nodes, but do communicate with nodes.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The mining process in bitcoin involves maintaining the blockchain through computer processing power.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Miners group and broadcast new transactions into blocks, which are then verified by the network.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Each block must contain a proof of work (PoW) to be accepted, involving finding a nonce number that, combined with the block content, produces a hash numerically smaller than the network's *difficulty target*.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] This PoW is simple to verify but hard to generate, requiring many attempts.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] PoW forms the basis of bitcoin's consensus mechanism.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The difficulty of generating a block is deterministically adjusted based on the mining power on the network by changing the difficulty target, which is recalibrated every 2,016 blocks (approximately two weeks) to maintain an average time of ten minutes between new blocks.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The process requires significant computational power and specialized hardware.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Miners who successfully create a new block with a valid nonce can collect transaction fees from the included transactions and a fixed reward in bitcoins.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] To claim this reward, a special transaction called a *coinbase* is included in the block, with the miner as the payee.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] All bitcoins in existence have been created through this type of transaction.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] This reward is halved every 210,000 blocks until ₿21 million have been issued in total, which is expected to occur around the year 2140.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Afterward, miners will only earn from transaction fees.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] These fees are determined by the transaction's size and the amount of data stored, measured in satoshis per byte.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The proof of work system and the chaining of blocks make blockchain modifications very difficult, as altering one block requires changing all subsequent blocks.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] As more blocks are added, modifying older blocks becomes increasingly challenging.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In case of disagreement, nodes trust the longest chain, which required the greatest amount of effort to produce.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] To tamper or censor the ledger, one needs to control the majority of the global hashrate.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The high cost required to reach this level of computational power secures the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The environmental impact of bitcoin mining is controversial and has attracted the attention of regulators, leading to restrictions or incentives in various jurisdictions.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] As of 2025, a non-peer-reviewed study by the Cambridge Centre for Alternative Finance (CCAF) estimated that bitcoin mining represented 0.5% of global electricity consumption and 0.08% of world greenhouse gas emissions, comparable to Slovakia's emissions.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] About half of the electricity used is generated through fossil fuels.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Moreover, mining hardware's short lifespan results in electronic waste.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In October 2025, the US was the largest mining country with 38% of the global bitcoin mining market share, followed by Russia (16%) and China (14%, despite all cryptocurrency trading and mining being banned there in 2021).
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Bitcoin is pseudonymous, with funds linked to addresses, not real-world identities.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] While the owners of these addresses are not directly identified, all transactions are public on the blockchain.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Patterns of use, like spending coins from multiple inputs, can hint at a common owner.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Public data can sometimes be matched with known address owners.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Bitcoin exchanges might also need to collect personal data as per legal requirements.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] For enhanced privacy, users can generate a new address for each transaction.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In the bitcoin network, each bitcoin is treated equally, ensuring basic fungibility.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] However, users and applications can choose to differentiate between bitcoins.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] While wallets and software treat all bitcoins the same, each bitcoin's transaction history is recorded on the blockchain.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] This public record allows for chain analysis, where users can identify and potentially reject bitcoins from controversial sources.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Gox froze accounts containing bitcoins identified as stolen.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Bitcoin wallets were the first cryptocurrency wallets, enabling users to store the information necessary to transact bitcoins.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The first wallet program, simply named *Bitcoin*, and sometimes referred to as the *Satoshi client*, was released in 2009 by Nakamoto as open-source software.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Bitcoin Core is among the best known clients.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Forks of Bitcoin Core exist such as Bitcoin Unlimited.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Wallets can be full clients, with a full copy of the blockchain to check the validity of mined blocks, or lightweight clients, just to send and receive transactions without a local copy of the entire blockchain.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Third-party internet services, called online wallets or hot wallets, store users' credentials on their servers, making them susceptible of hacks.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Cold storage protects bitcoins from such hacks by keeping private keys offline, either through specialized hardware wallets or paper printouts.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Nakamoto limited the block size to one megabyte.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The limited block size and frequency can lead to delayed processing of transactions, increased fees and a bitcoin scalability problem.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The Lightning Network, a second-layer routing network, is a potential scaling solution.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Research shows a trend towards centralization in bitcoin as miners join pools for stable income.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] If a single miner or pool controls more than 50% of the hashing power, it would allow them to censor transactions and double-spend coins.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In 2014, mining pool Ghash.io reached 51% mining power, causing safety concerns, but later voluntarily capped its power at 39.99% for the benefit of the whole network.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] A few entities also dominate other parts of the ecosystem such as the client software, online wallets, and simplified payment verification (SPV) clients.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Sociologist Nigel Dodd argues that the essence of the bitcoin ideology is to remove money from social, as well as governmental, control.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] *The Economist* describes bitcoin as "a techno-anarchist project to create an online version of cash, a way for people to transact without the possibility of interference from malicious governments or banks".
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] These philosophical ideas initially attracted libertarians and anarchists.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Money serves three purposes: a store of value, a medium of exchange, and a unit of account.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] According to *The Economist* in 2014, bitcoin functions best as a medium of exchange.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In 2015, *The Economist* noted that bitcoins had three qualities useful in a currency: they are "hard to earn, limited in supply and easy to verify".
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] However, a 2018 assessment by *The Economist* stated that cryptocurrencies met none of these three criteria.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Per some researchers, as of 2015, bitcoin functions more as a payment system than as a currency.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Shiller wrote that bitcoin has potential as a unit of account for measuring the relative value of goods, as with Chile's Unidad de Fomento, but that "Bitcoin in its present form... doesn't really solve any sensible economic problem".
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The legal status of bitcoin varies substantially from one jurisdiction to another.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Because of its decentralized nature and its global presence, regulating bitcoin is difficult.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] However, the use of bitcoin can be criminalized, and shutting down exchanges and the peer-to-peer economy in a given country would constitute a de facto ban.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The use of bitcoin by criminals has attracted the attention of financial regulators, legislative bodies, and law enforcement.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Nobel-prize winning economist Joseph Stiglitz says that bitcoin's anonymity encourages money laundering and other crimes.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] This is the main justification behind bitcoin bans.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] As of November 2021, nine countries applied an absolute ban (Algeria, Bangladesh, China, Egypt, Iraq, Morocco, Nepal, Qatar, and Tunisia) while another 42 countries had an implicit ban.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] According to Harvard Professor Kenneth Rogoff as of 2025, bitcoin is rarely used in regular transactions with merchants, but is popular in the informal economy and for criminal activities.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Prices are not usually quoted in bitcoin and trades involve conversions into fiat currencies.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Commonly cited reasons for not using bitcoin include high costs, the inability to process chargebacks, high price volatility, long transaction times, and transaction fees (especially for small purchases).
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] *Bloomberg* reported that bitcoin was being used for large-item purchases on the site Overstock.com and for cross-border payments to freelancers.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] As of 2015, there was little sign of bitcoin use in international remittances despite high fees charged by banks and Western Union.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] From September 2021 until January 2025, the Bitcoin Law made bitcoin a legal tender currency in El Salvador, alongside the US dollar.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The adoption had been criticized internationally and within El Salvador.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In 2022, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) urged El Salvador to reverse its decision.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] As of 2022, the use of Bitcoin in El Salvador remained low: 80% of businesses refused to accept it.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In 2025, El Salvador's government revoked bitcoin's status as legal tender currency in order to comply with conditions set by the IMF for a loan.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] El Salvador still describes bitcoin as "legal tender", but its acceptance is no longer obligitory (as it is with the US dollar) and the El Salvador government no longer accepts bitcoin for payment of taxes or fees.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In April 2022, the Central African Republic (CAR) adopted bitcoin as legal tender alongside the CFA franc, but repealed the reform one year later.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Bitcoin is also used by some governments.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] For instance, the Iranian government initially opposed cryptocurrencies, but later began using them to circumvent sanctions.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Since 2020, Iran has required local bitcoin miners to sell bitcoin to the Central Bank of Iran, allowing the central bank to use it for imports.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Some constituent states and local governments also accept tax payments in bitcoin, including Colorado in the US and Zug and Lugano in Switzerland.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] As of 2023, the US government owned more than $5 billion worth of seized bitcoin.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] As of 2018, the overwhelming majority of bitcoin transactions took place on cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Since 2014, regulated bitcoin funds also allow exposure to the asset or to futures as an investment.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Bitcoin is used as a store of value: individuals and companies such as the Winklevoss twins and Elon Musk's companies SpaceX and Tesla have each bought and sold hundreds of millions of dollars worth of bitcoin.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Bitcoin wealth is highly concentrated, with 0.01% holding 27% of in-circulation currency, as of 2021.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] As of March 2025, El Salvador had $550 million worth of bitcoin in its international reserves, about 6,102 coins.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Bitcoin, along with other cryptocurrencies, has been described as an economic bubble by several economists, including Nobel Prize in Economics laureates, such as Joseph Stiglitz, James Heckman, and Paul Krugman.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Another recipient of the prize, Robert Shiller, argues that bitcoin is rather a fad that may become an asset class.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] He describes its price growth as an "epidemic", driven by contagious narratives.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In 2024, Jean Tirole, also Nobel laureate, described bitcoin as a "pure bubble" as its intrinsic value is zero.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] According to him, some bubbles are long-lasting such as gold and fiat currencies, and it is impossible to predict whether bitcoin would implode like other financial bubbles or become an alternative to gold.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The same year, Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell described bitcoin as a digital competitor to gold but not to the dollar as he argued it is a highly volatile speculative asset not used as a form of payment.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In 2025, Kenneth Rogoff claimed that Krugman was wrong and that Bitcoin had value as it is competing with the dollar to become the means of exchange of the underground economy which represents 20% of the world's GDP.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] According to Rogoff, bitcoin is "the ideal currency for a more fragmented and uncertain global landscape" and it could become appealing to emerging-market central banks as a "politically neutral" reserve currency.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] According to research published in the *International Review of Financial Analysis* in 2018, bitcoin as an asset is highly volatile and does not behave like any other conventional asset.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] According to one 2022 analysis published in *The Journal of Alternative Investments*, bitcoin was less volatile than oil, silver, US Treasuries, and 190 stocks in the S&P 500 during and after the 2020 stock market crash.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The term *hodl* was created in December 2013 for holding bitcoin rather than selling it during periods of volatility.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] In 2014, economist Nouriel Roubini described bitcoin as a Ponzi scheme.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Legal scholar Eric Posner disagrees, however, as "a real Ponzi scheme takes fraud; bitcoin, by contrast, seems more like a collective delusion".
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] A 2014 World Bank report also concluded that bitcoin was not a deliberate Ponzi scheme.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Bitcoin markets operate 24 hours a day, seven days a week, contrasting with traditional financial markets that have fixed trading hours.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] Bitcoin prices show much higher volatility and respond strongly to both regulatory changes and market events.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The volume of bitcoin trading can fluctuate considerably among various exchanges and geographic regions.
[src:crypto-wallets/bitcoin] The daily transaction volume of bitcoin across all exchanges typically reaches $50 billion as of 2025.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] The company is led by CEO Peter Smith, one of its three founders, and co-CEO Lane Kasselman.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] The company's board members include Smith, co-founder Nicolas Cary, Tom Horton, Jim Messina, Joseph Otting, Manuel Stotz, Nicolas Brand, Timothy P.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] Between 2012 and February 2021, the company raised a total of $190 million in venture capital funding.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In March 2021, it raised an additional $300 million investment.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] Investors in the company include partners of DST Global, Lightspeed Venture Partners, VY Capital, GV, Baillie Gifford, Lakestar, Eldridge, Kyle Bass, Access Industries, Moore Strategic Ventures and Rovida Advisors.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] Blockchain.info was established by Ben Reeves in 2011.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] He launched a website which could be used to track bitcoin transactions.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] The website was a block explorer, a website that allowed bitcoin users to see the details of public cryptocurrency transactions if they have the identifying hash code for the transaction.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In early 2012, Reeves and Brian Armstrong, the co-founder of crypto-currency exchange Coinbase, applied to Y Combinator's summer class.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] They proposed a payment platform for bitcoin where users could keep a digital wallet, exchange other currencies for bitcoins for a percentage fee, and make payments in bitcoin.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] Due to different opinions they parted ways prior to attending Y Combinator.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] Reeves wanted to create a platform where users controlled access to their bitcoin information, while Armstrong felt that the platform should retain custody of the users wallets.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] After parting ways with Armstrong, Reeves continued to work on Blockchain.info.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] From 2013 to 2014, Blockchain's user base grew from 100,000 wallet users in early 2013 to 1.5 million in April 2014.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] By 2014, Blockchain.com was the most popular bitcoin wallet and was led by Nicolas Cary as CEO.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] It had acquired two companies, ZeroBlock in 2013, and RTBTC in early 2014, through which it added data analytics services, and brought these services together under one umbrella.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In December 2013, Blockchain.com acquired ZeroBlock, an app for bitcoin pricing.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] The following year, it acquired the data analytics platform RTBTC.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] It integrated RTBTC's technology with its existing services, establishing one platform offering cryptocurrency wallet, pricing and analytics, and the cryptocurrency explorer.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In February 2014, Apple Inc. removed the Blockchain.com app from the iOS App Store, prompting a public outcry in the bitcoin community, most notably within the Reddit community.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] At the time, it was the only bitcoin wallet app available for Apple users, as Apple had removed or denied other apps.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In July 2014, Apple reinstated the Blockchain.com app.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In 2014, Peter Smith joined the founding team as its CEO.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] The three founders, Reeves, Cary and Smith, worked from Reeves' flat in York and formally established the company when bitcoin investor Roger Ver provided initial funding.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] By October 2014, it had 2.3 million consumer wallets and raised $30.5 million in its first external fundraising round, with investors including Lightspeed Venture Partners and Mosaic Ventures.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] This was the biggest round of financing in the digital currency sector at that time.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] The World Economic Forum named the company as one of 2016's "Technology Pioneers".
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In 2017, the company carried out a second round of fundraising.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] It closed $40 million in funding that June and the company was valued at $280 million.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In 2018, Blockchain started selling services for institutional cryptocurrency.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In July 2019, Blockchain.com launched its cryptocurrency exchange and promoted it as faster than others.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In September 2020, the company joined the Coalition for App Fairness which aims to negotiate for better conditions for the inclusion of apps in app stores.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In mid-2018, the company acquired Tsukemen, an app-development startup company based in San Francisco.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In 2020 the company had 31 million users and as of 2021, there were 65 million Blockchain.com wallets and 28% of bitcoin transactions since 2012 were initiated or received by a Blockchain.com wallet.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In February 2021, Blockchain.com raised a $120 million funding round from investors including Moore Strategic Ventures, Kyle Bass, Access Industries, Rovida Advisors, Lightspeed Venture Partners, GV, Lakestar, and Eldridge.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] Including previous venture capital funding rounds, the company had raised $190 million altogether.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] One month later, the company announced a further $300 million fundraising round.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] One-third of the amount raised was funded by investment firm Baillie Gifford which invested $100 million.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] Based on the fundraising round, the company was valued at $5.2 billion.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In 2022, Blockchain.com's CEO wrote to shareholders informing them that Three Arrows Capital rapidly becoming insolvent meant a default impact of approximately $270 million worth of cryptocurrency and US dollar loans to Blockchain.com.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] The firm laid off 25% of its staff, about 150 people, on July 21.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In that same year, Blockchain.com partnered with the Dallas Cowboys, which became the first NFL team to add a digital currency platform as a sponsor.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] As of May 2023, Blockchain.com had over 31 million clients, with growth focused in countries such as Nigeria, Ghana, Colombia, Argentina, and Ukraine, according to the company's chief executive officer, Peter Smith.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] The company was also investing heavily in European countries and Singapore.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In November of that same year, Blockchain.com raised $110 million in Series E funding led by Kingsway Capital.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] The round also included investments from Baillie Gifford, Lakestar, Lightspeed Venture Partners, and Coinbase Ventures.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] Ending the year, in December 2023, reports by *Bloomberg* indicated that Blockchain.com sought to expand into Nigeria and Turkey within the first quarter of 2024, and to expand it's workforce by 25%.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] At that time, the company employed an estimated 300 people.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] Additionally, Blockchain.com hired staff to set up the company's hub in Paris and sought to create local entities across Europe, which were needed to adhere to regulations.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] To date, the exchange's European operations were managed through a London-based entity.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In 2025, Blockchain.com donated $5 million to MAGA Inc., a super PAC that supports Donald Trump.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] Also in that year, the company expressed interest in expanding to Africa, as multiple nations began to implement regulations surrounding cryptocurrencies.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In March 2026, Blockchain.com participated in equity fundraising and strategic partnership alongside British politician Nigel Farage for Stack BTC, a London-based company that acquires small British companies and invests surplus capital into bitcoin.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In the next month, Farage purchased £2 million worth of bitcoin, filming the transaction taking place at Blockchain.com's London offices.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In May 2026, Blockchain.com confidentially filed for an initial public offering with the United States Securities and Exchange Commission.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] As of that date, the company had facilitated $1.1 trillion in cryptocurrency transactions from millions of users across over 100 countries.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] As a cryptocurrency company, Blockchain.com provides a platform for holding, using, managing crypto assets, and exploring cryptocurrency transactions.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] It also develops financial services standards and infrastructure for cryptocurrencies.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] The company's platform provides market data and analytics.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] It follows cryptocurrency's aims of being decentralized and anonymous; some of its cryptocurrency products are managed by the end user and not accessible by Blockchain.com itself.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] Its main products are its cryptocurrency wallet, brokerage, block explorer, and institutional markets offering.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] As a brokerage, Blockchain.com executes trades for its users by utilizing internal stashes of crypto, or crypto from other exchanges, rather than a usual exchange, which matches buyers and sellers on a platform.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] Blockchain.com's revenue is created through transaction fees, subscriptions and services, and trading and venture investments.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In 2025, approximately 60% of its total revenue came from its brokerage and blockchain market services, which included providing liquidity for new token launches, and roughly 40% was through retail users.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] The company offers a hosted cryptocurrency wallet which is a method to store cryptocurrency in a digital file that can be accessed online.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] The wallet can be used with different cryptocurrencies and stablecoins.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] Its wallets can be used to send and receive digital currency transactions, as well as swap between different cryptocurrencies.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] Blockchain.com has a non-custodial wallet, meaning that it is controlled completely by the user and the company has no access to the wallet's data.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] Users access their wallet with a private key, a recovery phrase known only to the user.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] As of November 2025, Blockchain.com had around 39 million verified user wallets associated with its brokerage.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] In addition to its services for individuals, Blockchain.com also provides institutional investors with cryptocurrency-based financial services.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] The company's institutional markets business provides cryptocurrency lending, borrowing, trading and custody of financial assets.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] It also carries out over-the-counter transactions for large traders, acting as a broker to keep trades private and prevent price swings occurring based on market knowledge of the trades.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] The company operates a blockchain explorer that allows the user to see public cryptocurrency transactions and related information.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] This allows anyone who has a transaction's hash code to see the addresses of the wallets the transaction was sent from and received to, the amount of the transaction, and any fees.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] The tool can be used for analysis of transaction activity, cryptocurrency data, and analytics.
[src:crypto-wallets/blockchain-com] The company sells advertising on the otherwise free service.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Described as a conservative and law-abiding cryptocurrency exchange, Coinbase offers cryptocurrency products and services.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] As of 2025, the company operates as a remote-first company with no physical headquarters.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Coinbase was founded in June 2012 by Brian Armstrong, a former Airbnb engineer.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Armstrong enrolled in the Y Combinator startup incubator program and received a US$150,000 cash infusion.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Fred Ehrsam, a former Goldman Sachs trader, later joined as a co-founder after noticing Armstrong's posts on Reddit.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] British programmer and Blockchain.info co-founder Ben Reeves was originally supposed to be part of the Coinbase founding team, but parted ways with Armstrong just before the Y Combinator funding event, due to their different stands on how the Coinbase wallet should operate.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The company is named after coinbase transactions, which are special transactions that introduce cryptocurrency into circulation in proof of work cryptocurrencies.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In October 2012, the company launched the services to buy and sell bitcoins through bank transfers.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In May 2013, Coinbase received a US$5 million Series A investment led by Fred Wilson from the venture capital firm Union Square Ventures.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In December, the company received a US$25 million investment from the venture capital firm Andreessen Horowitz, Union Square Ventures (USV), and Ribbit Capital.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Olaf Carlson-Wee, a graduate from Vassar College, was hired as the first employee in the same year.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In 2014, Coinbase grew to one million users, acquired the blockchain explorer service Blockr and the web bookmarking company Kippt, secured insurance covering the value of bitcoin stored on their servers and launched the vault system for secure bitcoin storage.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Throughout 2014, the company also partnered with Overstock, Dell, Expedia, Dish Network, and Time Inc. allowing those firms to accept bitcoin payments.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In the same year, the company also added bitcoin payment processing capabilities to the traditional payment companies Stripe, Braintree, and PayPal.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In January 2014, Coinbase Global, Inc. was incorporated in Delaware as a holding company for Coinbase and its subsidiaries.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The corporate reorganization that saw Coinbase become a subsidiary of Coinbase Global was completed in April of that year.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In January 2015, Coinbase received a US$75 million investment, led by Draper Fisher Jurvetson, the New York Stock Exchange, USAA, and several banks.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Later in January, the company launched a U.S.-based bitcoin exchange for professional traders called Coinbase Exchange.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In September, Coinbase began to offer services in Canada and Singapore.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In May 2016, Coinbase rebranded the Coinbase Exchange, changing the name to Global Digital Asset Exchange (GDAX).
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In July, they added retail support for Ether.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Also, in July, they announced they would halt services in August after the closure of Canadian online payments service provider Vogogo.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In January and then March 2017, Coinbase obtained BitLicense and was licensed to trade in Ethereum and Litecoin from the New York State Department of Financial Services (DFS).
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In November, Coinbase was ordered by the U.S.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Internal Revenue Service (IRS) to report any users who had at least US$20,000 in transactions in a year.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] On December 19, Coinbase listed Bitcoin Cash, and the Coinbase platform experienced price abnormalities that led to an insider trading investigation.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] On February 23, 2018, Coinbase told approximately 13,000 affected customers that the company would be providing their taxpayer ID, name, birth date, address, and historical transaction records from 2013 to 2015 to the IRS within 21 days.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In March, Coinbase appointed Emilie Choi, a former LinkedIn executive, as Vice President of Corporate and Business Development.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] She was promoted to the role of president and chief operating officer in May 2019.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] On March 26, 2018, Coinbase announced their intention to add support for Ethereum ERC-20 tokens.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] On April 5, 2018, Coinbase announced that it had formed an early-stage venture fund, Coinbase Ventures, focusing on investment into blockchain- and cryptocurrency-related companies.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] On May 16, Coinbase Ventures announced its first investment in Compound Labs, a start-up building Ethereum smart contracts similar to money markets.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] On May 23, GDAX was rebranded as Coinbase Pro.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Also in May, Coinbase launched Prime, a platform dedicated to institutional customers.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In August, Amazon cloud executive Tim Wagner joined Coinbase as vice president of engineering.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In September, Coinbase, along with Circle and bitcoin miner company Bitmain, was part of a consortium called Centre that launched a digital coin called USD Coin, pegged to the U.S. dollar.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In January 2019, Coinbase stopped all trading on Ethereum Classic due to a suspicion of an attack on the network.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In February, Coinbase announced that it had acquired "blockchain intelligence platform" Neutrino, an Italy-based startup, for an undisclosed price.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The acquisition raised concern among some Coinbase users based on Neutrino founders' connection to the HackingTeam, which has been accused of providing internet surveillance technology to governments with poor human rights records.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] This reported attack used spear-phishing and social engineering tactics (including sending fake e-mails from compromised email accounts and creating a landing page at the University of Cambridge) and two Firefox browser zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] One of the Firefox vulnerabilities could allow an attacker to escalate privileges from JavaScript on a browser page (CVE-2019–11707) and the other, could allow the attacker to escape the browser sandbox and execute code on the host computer (CVE-2019–11708).
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Coinbase's security team detected and blocked the attack, the network was not compromised, and no cryptocurrency was stolen.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In May 2020, during the COVID-19 pandemic, Coinbase announced it was shifting completely to remote work and would no longer recognize a formal headquarters.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Also in May, the company announced the acquisition of New York-based digital asset trading firm Tagomi for a price between US$75 and US$100 million.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In June, Coinbase received internal backlash after CEO Brian Armstrong initially refused to make a statement about Black Lives Matter, citing the company's apolitical culture, but Armstrong later reversed his course on Twitter.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In September, Armstrong published a blog post emphasizing that Coinbase would not engage in social activism, citing that such activism had hurt other technology firms such as Google and Facebook, and offered a severance package for those who disagreed with this direction.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The company also faced complaints by employees saying they were treated unfairly due to their race or gender.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In October, Coinbase announced the launch of a Visa debit card program.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] That same month, Coinbase announced that it was establishing a business presence in India and hiring employees for IT services, including engineering, software development and customer support operations.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The company also announced plans to open a physical office in Hyderabad.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In April 2021, with its final earnings release before its April 14 direct listing, Coinbase reported a nine-fold increase in first-quarter revenue, to US$1.8 billion, up from US$90.6 million the previous year.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The jump was attributed to the increase in the price of bitcoin over that period.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] On April 14, 2021, Coinbase became a public company on the Nasdaq exchange via a direct stock listing.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Before the listing, Nasdaq set a reference price of US$250 a share, giving the company an estimated value of US$47 billion.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] At the end of its first day of trading, Coinbase closed at US$328.28 per share.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In May, the company's chief people officer published a blog post announcing that Coinbase was eliminating salary and equity negotiations during recruiting, citing salary disparities with women and minorities.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The announcement said that "all employees in the same position, in the same location, receive the same salary and equity offer".
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In June, Coinbase added Dogecoin to its tradable assets for Coinbase Pro users.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Securities and Exchange Commission reportedly threatened to sue Coinbase if the company decided to launch a cryptocurrency lending product called Lend.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The company initially responded in a blog post that it was confused for being singled out by the SEC, but later announced it had cancelled the planned launch.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Technology publication TechCrunch covered the story and noted the existence of similar cryptocurrency lending products already on the market.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In November, Coinbase made its first acquisition in India by purchasing AI-powered support platform Agara for an estimated US$40 to US$50 million.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The company stated that it would utilize Agara's technology to automate its customer experience tools.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] On December 15 a display glitch vastly inflated balances so that numerous users were incorrectly shown to be trillionaires.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In February 2022, Coinbase's 60-second commercial during Super Bowl LVI involved a QR code to direct viewers to the company's webpage and was effective, according to Adweek.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In the following month, in response to the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, Coinbase blocked 25,000 cryptocurrency wallet addresses related to Russia.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Coinbase began operations in India in April 2022.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The company initially relied on Unified Payments Interface to allow users to convert rupees to cryptocurrencies, but ceased using UPI after a statement released by the National Payments Corporation of India indicating it was "not aware of any crypto exchange using UPI".
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] This statement forced Coinbase to suspend most of its business in India.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Users in India cannot convert rupees into cryptocurrency but can trade between different cryptocurrencies.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In May 2022, Coinbase-backed Mara raised US$23 million to build an African crypto Exchange.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] On June 14, 2022, the company announced it would be laying off approximately 18% of its workforce, about 1,100 full-time jobs, amid the global downturn in cryptocurrencies and services.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In August 2022, Coinbase announced a partnership with BlackRock, a venture which allows BlackRock clients to use their Aladdin investment management system to oversee their exposure to bitcoin along with other portfolio assets, and to facilitate trading on Coinbase's exchange.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In October 2022, Coinbase entered into a partnership with Google Cloud Platform that would allow the latter's customers to pay for cloud services with cryptocurrencies supported by Coinbase Commerce.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Coinbase also agreed to transfer its data-related applications from Amazon Web Services to Google Cloud.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] On January 10, 2023, Coinbase announced it would be laying off around 950 employees, incurring restructuring expenses of up to US$163 million.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Citing the possibility of "further contagion" following the collapse of the FTX exchange, Brian Armstrong said Coinbase would be "shutting down several projects where we have a lower probability of success".
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In February 2023, Coinbase launched its own layer 2 blockchain on Ethereum, based on MIT-licensed OP Stack of layer-2 blockchain Optimism.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In April 2023, the company announced that its Coinbase Bermuda division had been licensed to operate cryptocurrencies in Bermuda.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The next month, the company launched the Bermuda-based crypto derivatives exchange, named Coinbase International Exchange, allowing non-U.S. customers to trade bitcoin and Ethereum futures.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In July 2023, Coinbase was reported to have leased 40,000 sq.ft. of office space in Mountain View, California within the Bay Area.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] This followed the company's prior closing of its San Francisco headquarters amid its transformation to become a remote-first and headquarterless company.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In December 2024, Coinbase added Apple Pay support to its *Onramp platform* (formerly known as *Coinbase Pay*), allowing users of third-party apps to fund their crypto purchases directly through Apple's payment service.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The supported cryptocurrencies included bitcoin, ether, Dogecoin and others present on the crypto exchange.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] On 22 March 2023, Coinbase received a Wells notice from the U.S.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) signalling that the SEC intended to begin an enforcement action over Coinbase's staking products.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Coinbase responded by calling the investigation "cursory", and stated that it would continue to operate as usual.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The next month, Coinbase sued the SEC asking a federal court to force the regulator to respond to a rulemaking petition the company submitted last year asking it to make clear regulations pertaining cryptocurrencies.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In June 2023, the SEC said it was suing Coinbase, alleging that the company had been acting as an unregistered broker, exchange and clearing agency since 2019, requesting that the company be "permanently restrained and enjoined" from doing so.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The SEC also alleged that Coinbase never registered its staking service as required by U.S. securities laws.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In February 2025 following the election of Donald Trump, the SEC dismissed its lawsuit against Coinbase, putting an end to a legal battle between the two.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In March 2025, Coinbase said it was the largest node operator on the Ethereum network, controlling 11.42% of all staked Ether (ETH).
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In May 2025, Coinbase disclosed an extortion attempt where cybercriminals bribed rogue overseas support agents to steal customer data for social engineering attacks.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The stolen data included personal and account information, but no passwords, private keys, or funds.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Coinbase refused to pay the $20 million ransom that was asked and instead offered a $20 million reward for information leading to the attackers' conviction.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The company said "less than 1 per cent" of its data was impacted.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] On May 15, 2025, Coinbase announced it expected the attack would cost the company up to $400 million.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] *Wired* reported that Coinbase would reimburse customers up to $400 million.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] On May 8, 2025, Coinbase announced the acquisition of Deribit, a Dubai-based cryptocurrency derivatives exchange, for $700 million in cash and $2.2 billion worth of Coinbase stock.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Coinbase was included in the S&P 500 index on May 19, 2025.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In June 2025, Coinbase initiated establishing an office in Charlotte for its compliance and customer support teams.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The company also maintained offices in San Francisco and New York, and employed nearly 4,000 people with roughly 95% working remotely.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In October 2025, eight months after the SEC lawsuit was dismissed under the Trump administration, Coinbase was one of the donors who funded the White House's East Wing demolition, and planned building of a ballroom.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] That same month, the company reported it was holding digital assets worth $516 billion on its platform.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In May 2026, Coinbase announced it was laying off 14% of its staff, with non-technical teams now shipping production code.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] This strategy was widely criticized by its users and press for its unorthodox nature.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] As of 2025, Coinbase operates the largest U.S. based cryptocurrency exchange with over 108 million customers.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] It offers products for retail and institutional cryptocurrency investors, and other users including merchants and small businesses.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Additionally, Coinbase provides *Coinbase Developer Platform* for developers and non-technical users, which facilitates "on-chain" actions like balance checks, ETH testnet requests, and asset transfers.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] These functionalities allow the users to experiment with autonomous blockchain operations, aiming to improve the experience while executing smart contract transactions and other decentralized actions.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The company also provides an application programming interface (API) for developers and merchants to build applications and accept payments in digital currencies.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Although cryptocurrencies can assure anonymous trade *in principle*, Coinbase trades are not anonymous.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Registered users are required to provide their taxpayer identification, and the transactions are reported to the IRS.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Also, even though Coinbase offers more than 250 different cryptocurrencies to U.S. customers as of 2023, it does not trade Monero and other cryptocurrencies with enhanced anonymity protection due to the know your customer (KYC) requirements in accordance with anti–money laundering regulations.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] From 2021 to 2025, Coinbase operated as a remote-first company and has no physical headquarters.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In 2025, Coinbase leased a large office space in San Francisco to serve as a physical headquarters and operations hub.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In April 2019, a U.K. corporate filing stated that Coinbase's non-U.S. revenue grew 20 percent to €153 million (US$173 million) in 2018 resulting in a net profit of €6.6 million.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] CEO Zeeshan Feroz said the company's non-U.S. operations accounted for nearly one-third of the company's overall revenue and *Reuters* estimated that the company's global revenue totalled "around US$520 million" in 2018.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In 2021, as part of its SEC filing to go public, Coinbase reported 43 million verified users, 7,000 institutions, and 115,000 ecosystem partners in over 100 countries.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] It also reported net revenue of US$1.14 billion in 2020, up from US$483 million the previous year.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The company also reported a net income of US$322 million after posting a loss in 2019.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Out of the US$782 billion worth of assets on the crypto market, some US$90 billion worth were held on the Coinbase platform.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The company reported a net loss of US$1.1 billion in the second quarter of 2022, a record for Coinbase.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] As of 2025, Coinbase is the world's largest custodian of bitcoin, holding over 12% of all bitcoin in existence.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] It also holds over 11% of all staked Ether and other digital assets like solana.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In its 2024 annual report, the company said it was managing digital assets worth US$404 billion on its platform.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Coinbase has been described as a conservative and law-abiding cryptocurrency exchange, in comparison to its peers in the sector.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] As of 2025, Coinbase maintains an "A+" rating by the Better Business Bureau.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Earlier, from 2018 to 2023, the company received an "F" rating from the bureau due to poor customer service.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Common customer complaints included being locked out of their accounts despite providing the required information for reinstatement, as well as finding it "nearly impossible" to reach support when assistance was needed.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] On February 16, 2018, Coinbase admitted that some customers were overcharged in error for credit and debit purchases of cryptocurrencies.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The problem was initiated when banks and card issuers changed the merchant category code (MCC) for cryptocurrency purchases earlier that month.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] This meant that cryptocurrency payments would now be processed as "cash advances", meaning that banks and credit card issuers could begin charging customers cash advance fees for cryptocurrency purchases.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Customers who purchased cryptocurrency on their exchange between January 22 and February 11, 2018, could have been affected.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] At first, Visa blamed Coinbase, telling the *Financial Times* on February 16 that it had "not made any systems changes that would result in the duplicate transactions cardholders are reporting".
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] However, the latest statement from Visa and Worldpay on the Coinbase blog clarifies: "This issue was not caused by Coinbase".
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The article also noted that the company was subsequently increasing its customer service staff to reduce wait times.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In March 2021, Coinbase agreed to pay US$6.5 million to settle regulatory claims that it had reported misleading information about its trading volumes.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In December 2021, CNBC reported that Coinbase froze the cryptocurrency GYEN due to a sudden price spike, resulting in many traders losing money.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] According to the complaint filed in *SEC v.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Wahi,* Ishan Wahi allegedly shared information that certain tokens were about to be listed by Coinbase with Nikhil Wahi and Ramani, who then allegedly acted upon that information to make trades for an alleged illicit profit over US$1.5 million.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] According to federal prosecutors, Ishan Wahi purchased a one-way ticket to India upon being summoned by Coinbase to the company's Seattle office for a meeting.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Wahi was subsequently intercepted by law enforcement from boarding a May 16 flight to India.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Coinbase's chief security officer, Philip Martin, noted that the company provided prosecutors with information from an internal investigation.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] On January 10, 2023, Nikhil Wahi was sentenced to ten months in prison after he admitted to making trades based on confidential information from Coinbase.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] District Judge Loretta Preska said Wahi's crime was "not an isolated error in judgment".
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Ishan Wahi originally pleaded not guilty but entered a guilty plea on February 7, 2023.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] On May 9, 2023, Ishan Wahi was sentenced to two years in prison and ordered to forfeit various crypto assets that he received in connection with the scheme.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In January 2023, Coinbase agreed to pay a US$50 million penalty to the New York State Department of Financial Services (NYDFS) over allegations that the cryptocurrency exchange broke anti-money laundering laws.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The company was also required to invest an additional US$50 million in its compliance program to help prevent future violations.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] According to the NYDFS, Coinbase was unable to keep up with the number of alerts from its transaction monitoring system, a tool that was supposed to detect suspicious activity on the trading platform.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Coinbase allegedly amassed a backlog of over 100,000 alerts, resulting in the company failing to report and investigate suspicious transactions in a timely manner.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] That same month, the Dutch Central Bank (DNB) fined Coinbase €3.3 million for failing to obtain the correct registration in the Netherlands before offering services.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Coinbase said in response that it disagreed with the DNB's decision, which it said "includes no criticism of our actual services" and was considering an appeal.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] In July 2024, Coinbase's U.K. branch was fined £3.5 million by the British regulator Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) after the former's breach of the voluntary agreement brokered between the two in October 2020.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] According to the voluntary agreement, Coinbase had agreed to not accept new users that the regulator considered high-risk.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] The FCA said that breaches of the agreement increased the risk that criminals could use Coinbase to launder the proceeds of crime.
[src:crypto-wallets/coinbase] Coinbase stated in response that it had unintentionally onboarded a number of customers between October 2020 and October 2023 who were classified as high-risk and that those customers represented 0.34% of all customers on-boarded.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] A **cryptocurrency wallet** is a device, physical medium, program or an online service which stores the public and/or private keys for cryptocurrency transactions.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] In addition to this basic function of storing the keys, a cryptocurrency wallet more often offers the functionality of encrypting and/or signing information.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Signing can for example result in executing a smart contract, a cryptocurrency transaction (see "bitcoin transaction" image), identification, or legally signing a 'document' (see "application form" image).
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] In 2008 bitcoin was introduced as the first cryptocurrency following the principle outlined by Satoshi Nakamoto in the paper “Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System.” The project was described as an electronic payment system using cryptographic proof instead of trust.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] It also mentioned using cryptographic proof to verify and record transactions on a blockchain.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] The first wallet program, simply named *Bitcoin*, and sometimes referred to as the *Satoshi client*, was released in January 2009 by Satoshi Nakamoto as open-source software.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] In version 0.5 the client moved from the wxWidgets user interface toolkit to Qt, and the whole bundle was referred to as *Bitcoin-Qt*.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] After the release of version 0.9, the software bundle was renamed *Bitcoin Core* to distinguish itself from the underlying network.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Bitcoin Core is, perhaps, the best known implementation or client.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Forks of Bitcoin Core exist, such as Bitcoin XT, Bitcoin Unlimited, and Parity Bitcoin.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Software wallets is a broad category of software applications that allow users to manage and transfer digital assets, and sign messages.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] They can be run as desktop apps, mobile apps, web extensions, or web wallets.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] There are several modes in which software wallets can operate.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] They have an inverse relationship with regard to trustlessness and computational requirements.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Third-party internet services called *online wallets* or *webwallets* offer similar functionality but may be easier to use.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] In this case, credentials to access funds are stored with the online wallet provider rather than on the user's hardware.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] As a result, the user must have complete trust in the online wallet provider.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] A malicious provider or a breach in server security may cause entrusted crypto to be stolen.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] An example of such a security breach occurred with Mt.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] A paper wallet with the address visible for adding or checking stored funds.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] The part of the page containing the private key is folded over and sealed.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] A part of the address is visible through a transparent part of the hologram.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] "Cold storage" simply means keeping the private keys out of reach of hackers by storing or generating them on a device that is not connected to the internet.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] The credentials necessary to spend crypto can be stored offline in a number of different ways, from simple paper printouts of private keys, to specialized hardware wallets.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] A paper wallet is created with a keypair generated on a computer with no internet connection; the private key is written or printed onto the paper and then erased from the computer.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] The paper wallet can then be stored in a safe physical location for later retrieval.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Physical wallets can also take the form of metal token coins with a private key accessible under a security hologram in a recess struck on the reverse side.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] The security hologram self-destructs when removed from the token, showing that the private key has been accessed.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Originally, these tokens were struck in brass and other base metals, but later used precious metals as bitcoin grew in value and popularity.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Coins with stored face value as high as ₿1,000 have been struck in gold.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] The British Museum's coin collection includes four specimens from the earliest series of funded bitcoin tokens; one is currently on display in the museum's money gallery.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] In 2013, a Utah manufacturer of these tokens was ordered by the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN) to register as a money services business before producing any more funded bitcoin tokens.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] A hardware "wallet" is a small and portable computer peripheral that signs transactions as requested by the user.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] These devices store private keys and carry out signing and encryption internally, and do not share any sensitive information with the host computer except already signed (and thus unalterable) transactions.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Because hardware wallets never expose their private keys, even computers that may be compromised by malware do not have a vector to access or steal them.The user sets a passcode when setting up a hardware signer.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] As hardware signers are tamper-resistant, without the passcode the assets cannot be accessed.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] In contrast to simple cryptocurrency wallets requiring just one party to sign a transaction, multi-sig wallets require multiple parties to sign a transaction.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Multisignature wallets are designed to increase security by requiring a predefined threshold of signatures from independent private keys to authorize any transaction.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] In deterministic multisig wallets, a hierarchy of keys (often following a dedicated path such as `m/48'`) allows multiple participants to derive compatible public keys from a single master seed while maintaining independent private key control.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] There are various use cases for multisignature wallets, including enhanced security, treasury management, partnership management, escrow services, inheritance planning, regulatory compliance and backup recovery.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] A cryptocurrency wallet works by a theoretical or random number being generated and used with a length that depends on the algorithm size of the cryptocurrency's technology requirements.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] The number is converted to a private key using the specific requirements of the cryptocurrency cryptography algorithm requirement.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] A public key is then generated from the private key using whichever cryptographic algorithm is required.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] The private key is used by the owner to access and send cryptocurrency and is private to the owner, whereas the public key is to be shared to any third party to receive cryptocurrency.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Up to this stage no computer or electronic device is required and all key pairs can be mathematically derived and written down by hand.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] The private key and public key pair (known as an address) are not known by the blockchain or anyone else.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] The blockchain will only record the transaction of the public address when cryptocurrency is sent to it, thus recording in the blockchain ledger the transaction of the public address.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Collision (two or more wallets having the same private key) is theoretically possible, since keys can be generated without being used for transactions, and are therefore offline until recorded in the blockchain ledger.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] However, this possibility is effectively negated because the theoretical probability of two or more private keys being the same is extremely low.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] The number of possible wallets and thus private keys is extremely high, so duplicating or hacking a certain key would be inconceivable.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] In modern convention a seed phrase is now utilised which is a random 12 to 24 (or even greater) list of dictionary words which is an unencrypted form of the private key.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] (Words are easier to memorize than numerals).
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] When online, exchange and hardware wallets are generated using random numbers, and the user is asked to supply a seed phrase.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] If the wallet is misplaced, damaged or compromised, the seed phrase can be used to re-access the wallet and associated keys and cryptocurrency *in toto*.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] A number of technologies known as wallets exist that store the key value pair of private and public key known as wallets.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] A wallet hosts the details of the key pair making cryptocurrency transactions possible.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Multiple methods exist for storing keys or seeds in a wallet.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] A *brainwallet* or *brain wallet* is a type of wallet in which one memorizes a passcode (a private key or seed phrase).
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Brainwallets may be attractive due to plausible deniability or protection against governmental seizure, but are vulnerable to password guessing (especially large-scale offline guessing).
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Several hundred brainwallets exist on the Bitcoin blockchain, but most of them have been drained, sometimes repeatedly.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] DApp browsers are specialized software that supports decentralized applications.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] DApp browsers are considered to be the browsers of Web3 and are the gateway to access the decentralized applications which are based on blockchain technology.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] That means all DApp browsers must have a unique code system to unify all the different codes of the DApps.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] While crypto wallets are focused on the exchange, purchase, sale of digital assets and support narrowly targeted applications, the browsers support different kinds of applications of various formats, including exchange, games, NFTs marketplaces, etc.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] In addition to the basic function of storing the keys, a cryptocurrency wallet may also have one or more of the following characteristics.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] A simple cryptocurrency wallet contains pairs of public and private cryptographic keys.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] The keys can be used to track ownership, receipt or spend cryptocurrencies.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] A public key allows others to make payments to the address derived from it, whereas a private key enables the spending of cryptocurrency from that address.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] The cryptocurrency itself is not in the wallet.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] In the case of bitcoin and cryptocurrencies derived from it, the cryptocurrency is decentrally stored and maintained in a publicly available distributed ledger called the *blockchain*.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Multi-chain wallets are designed to support multiple blockchain networks, enabling users to store, manage, and transact different types of cryptocurrencies from a single interface.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Unlike single-chain wallets, which are limited to a specific blockchain, multi-chain wallets provide a unified experience for handling various assets.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] These wallets enhance convenience and security by reducing the need for multiple wallet applications and providing integrated features for multiple digital assets.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Popular multi-chain wallets include Trust Wallet, Klever Wallet and Exodus, each offering unique features and support for multiple blockchains, therefore, hundreds of cryptocurrencies.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Some wallets are specifically designed to be compatible with a framework.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] The European Union is creating an eIDAS compatible European Self-Sovereign Identity Framework (ESSIF) which runs on the European Blockchain Services Infrastructure (EBSI).
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] The EBSI wallet is designed to (securely) provide information, an eID and to sign 'transactions'.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] A sequential deterministic wallet utilizes a simple method of generating addresses from a known starting string or "seed".
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] This would utilize a cryptographic hash function, e.g.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] SHA-256 (seed + n), where n is an ASCII-coded number that starts from 1 and increments as additional keys are needed.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] The hierarchical deterministic (HD) wallet was publicly described in BIP32.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] As a deterministic wallet, it derives keys from a single master root seed, but instead of having a single "chain" of key pairs, an HD wallet supports multiple independent key pair chains.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] This allows a single seed to be used to generate an entire tree of key pairs with a stratified structure.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] BIP39 proposed the use of a set of human-readable words to derive the seed used to generate a wallet’s master private key.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] This mnemonic phrase allows for easier wallet backup and recovery, due to all keys of a wallet being derivable from a single plaintext string.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] In a non-deterministic wallet, each key is randomly generated independently and is not derived from a common seed.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Therefore, any backups of the wallet must store each and every private key used as an address, as well as a buffer of future keys that may have already been issued as addresses but have not yet received payments.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] A wallet can also have known or unknown vulnerabilities.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] A supply chain attack or side-channel attack are ways of introducing vulnerabilities.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] In extreme cases even a computer which is not connected to any network can be hacked.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] To mitigate the risk of crypto wallet hacking, one can choose for a cold wallet, which remains offline and disconnected from the internet.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] A cold wallet refers to a physical device, such as a pen drive, that is utilized as a secure storage medium for transferring money from a hot wallet.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] When using a merchant site that accepts server-side digital wallets, customers enter their name, payment, and delivery information.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Following the purchase, the customer is requested to register for a wallet with a user name and password for future purchases.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Wallets are free for consumers but cost retailers.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] Wallet sellers may receive a portion of merchant purchases made through their wallets.
[src:crypto-wallets/cryptocurrency-wallet] In other circumstances, digital wallet vendors conduct cardholder-merchant transactions for a set fee.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] A **mnemonic device** (/nəˈmɒnɪk/ *nə-MON-ik*), **memory trick** or **memory device** is any learning technique that aids information retention or retrieval in the human memory, often by associating the information with something that is easier to remember.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] It makes use of elaborative encoding, retrieval cues and imagery as specific tools to encode information in a way that allows for efficient storage and retrieval.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] It aids original information in becoming associated with something more accessible or meaningful—which in turn provides better retention of the information.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Commonly encountered mnemonics are often used for lists and in auditory form such as short poems, acronyms, initialisms or memorable phrases.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] They can also be used for other types of information and in visual or kinesthetic forms.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Their use is based on the observation that the human mind more easily remembers spatial, personal, surprising, physical, sexual, humorous and otherwise "relatable" information rather than more abstract or impersonal forms of information.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Ancient Greeks and Romans distinguished between two types of memory: the "natural" memory and the "artificial" memory.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The former is inborn and is the one that everyone uses instinctively.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The latter in contrast has to be trained and developed through the learning and practice of a variety of mnemonic techniques.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Mnemonic systems are techniques or strategies consciously used to improve memory.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] They help use information already stored in long-term memory to make memorization an easier task.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Mnemonic devices were much cultivated by Greek sophists and philosophers and are frequently referred to by Plato and Aristotle.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Philosopher Charmadas was famous for his outstanding memory and for his ability to memorize whole books and then recite them.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] In later times, the poet Simonides was credited for development of these techniques, perhaps for no reason other than that the power of his memory was famous.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Cicero, who attaches considerable importance to the art, but more to the principle of order as the best help to memory, speaks of Carneades (perhaps Charmades) of Athens and Metrodorus of Scepsis as distinguished examples of people who used well-ordered images to aid the memory.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The Romans valued such helps in order to support facility in public speaking.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The Greek and the Roman system of mnemonics was founded on the use of mental places and signs or pictures, known as "topical" mnemonics.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The most usual method was to choose a large house, of which the apartments, walls, windows, statues, furniture, etc., were each associated with certain names, phrases, events or ideas, by means of symbolic pictures.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] To recall these, an individual had only to search over the apartments of the house until discovering the places where images had been placed by the imagination.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Therefore, if it were desired to fix in the memory the date of the invention of printing (1436), an imaginary book, or some other symbol of printing, would be placed in the thirty-sixth quadrate or memory-place of the fourth room of the first house of the historic district of the town.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Except that the rules of mnemonics are referred to by Martianus Capella, nothing further is known regarding the practice until the 13th century.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Among the voluminous writings of Roger Bacon is a tractate *De arte memorativa*.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] About the end of the 15th century, Peter of Ravenna (b.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] 1448) provoked such astonishment in Italy by his mnemonic feats that he was believed by many to be a necromancer.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] His *Phoenix artis memoriae* (Venice, 1491, 4 vols.) went through as many as nine editions, the seventh being published at Cologne in 1608.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] About the end of the 16th century, Lambert Schenkel (*Gazophylacium*, 1610), who taught mnemonics in France, Italy and Germany, similarly surprised people with his memory.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] He was denounced as a sorcerer by the University of Louvain, but in 1593 he published his tractate *De memoria* at Douai with the sanction of that celebrated theological faculty.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The most complete account of his system is given in two works by his pupil Martin Sommer, published in Venice in 1619.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] 1628?) published *Mnemonica; sive ars reminiscendi*, containing a clear statement of the principles of topical or local mnemonics.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Giordano Bruno included a *memoria technica* in his treatise *De umbris idearum,* as part of his study of the *ars generalis* of Llull.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Other writers of this period are the Florentine Publicius (1482); Johannes Romberch (1533); Hieronimo Morafiot, *Ars memoriae* (1602);and B.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] In 1648 Stanislaus Mink von Wennsshein revealed what he called the "most fertile secret" in mnemonics—using consonants for figures, thus expressing numbers by words (vowels being added as required), in order to create associations more readily remembered.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The philosopher Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz adopted an alphabet very similar to that of Wennsshein for his scheme of a form of writing common to all languages.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Wennsshein's method was adopted with slight changes afterward by the majority of subsequent "original" systems.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] It was modified and supplemented by Richard Grey (1694–1771), a priest who published a *Memoria technica* in 1730.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Wennsshein's method is comparable to a Hebrew system by which letters also stand for numerals, and therefore words for dates.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] To assist in retaining the mnemonical words in the memory, they were formed into memorial lines.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Such strange words in difficult hexameter scansion, are by no means easy to memorise.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The vowel or consonant, which Grey connected with a particular figure, was chosen arbitrarily.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] A later modification was made in 1806 Gregor von Feinaigle, a German monk from Salem near Constance.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] While living and working in Paris, he expounded a system of mnemonics in which (as in Wennsshein) the numerical figures are represented by letters chosen due to some similarity to the figure or an accidental connection with it.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] This alphabet was supplemented by a complicated system of localities and signs.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Feinaigle, who apparently did not publish any written documentation of this method, travelled to England in 1811.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The following year one of his pupils published *The New Art of Memory* (1812), giving Feinaigle's system.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] In addition, it contains valuable historical material about previous systems.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Other mnemonists later published simplified forms, as the more complicated mnemonics were generally abandoned.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Methods founded chiefly on the so-called laws of association (cf.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Mental association) were taught with some success in Germany.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Songs and jingles can be used as a mnemonic.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] A common example is how children remember the alphabet by singing the ABCs.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The first letter of each word is combined into a new word.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The first letter of each word is combined to form a phrase or sentence – e.g.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] " for the colours of the rainbow, or "Shake my hand, Evil Octopus!" for the Great Lakes.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] A model is used to help recall information.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Applications of this method involve the use of diagrams, cycles, graphs, and flowcharts to help understand or memorize an idea. e.g.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] to show the different parts of a five-act dramatic structure.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] " (most Latin nouns of the second declension ending in -er drop the -e in all of the oblique cases except the vocative, these are the exceptions).
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The method of note organization can be used as a memorization technique.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Applications of this method involve the use of flash cards and lists.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Flash cards are used by putting a question or word on one side of a paper and the answer or definition on the other side of the paper.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Lists involve the organization of data from broad to detailed. e.g.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The information is constructed into a picture.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] is connected to knowledge already known.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] allow the user to create unique associations in an imagined space.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] A wide range of mnemonics are used for several purposes.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The most commonly used mnemonics are those for lists, numerical sequences, foreign-language acquisition, and medical treatment for patients with memory deficits.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] A common mnemonic technique for remembering a list is to create an easily remembered acronym.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Another is to create a memorable phrase with words which share the same first letter(s) (i.e.: the same initialism) as the list members.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Mnemonic techniques can be applied to most memorization of novel materials.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Mnemonic phrases or poems can be used to encode numeric sequences by various methods, one common one is to create a new phrase in which the number of letters in each word represents the according digit of pi.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] For example, the first 15 digits of the mathematical constant pi (3.14159265358979) can be encoded as "Now I need a drink, alcoholic of course, after the heavy lectures involving quantum mechanics"; "Now", having 3 letters, represents the first number, 3.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Piphilology is the practice dedicated to creating mnemonics for pi.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Another is used for "calculating" the multiples of 9 up to 9 × 10 using one's fingers.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Begin by holding out both hands with all fingers stretched out.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Now count left to right the number of fingers that indicates the multiple.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] For example, to figure 9 × 4, count four fingers from the left, ending at your left-hand index finger.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Bend this finger down and count the remaining fingers.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Fingers to the left of the bent finger represent tens, fingers to the right are ones.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] There are three fingers to the left and six to the right, which indicates 9 × 4 = 36.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] For remembering the rules in adding and multiplying two signed numbers, Balbuena and Buayan (2015) made the letter strategies LAUS (like signs, add; unlike signs, subtract) and LPUN (like signs, positive; unlike signs, negative), respectively.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Mnemonics may be helpful in learning foreign languages, for example by transposing difficult foreign words with words in a language the learner knows already, also called "cognates" which are very common in Romance languages and other Germanic languages.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] A useful such technique is to find linkwords, words that have the same pronunciation in a known language as the target word, and associate them visually or auditorially with the target word.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] For example, in trying to assist the learner to remember *ohel* (אוהל‎), the Hebrew word for *tent*, the linguist Ghil'ad Zuckermann proposes the memorable sentence "*Oh hell*, there's a raccoon in my *tent*".
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The memorable sentence "There's a *fork* in *Ma's leg*" helps the learner remember that the Hebrew word for *fork* is **mazleg** (מזלג‎).
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Similarly, to remember the Hebrew word **bayit** (בית‎), meaning *house*, one can use the sentence "that's a lovely *house*, I'd like to *buy it*." The linguist Michel Thomas taught students to remember that **estar** is the Spanish word for *to be* by using the phrase "to be a star".
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Another Spanish example is by using the mnemonic "Vin Diesel Has Ten Weapons" to teach irregular command verbs in the you (*tú*) form.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Spanish verb forms and tenses are regularly seen as the hardest part of learning the language.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] With a high number of verb tenses, and many verb forms that are not found in English, Spanish verbs can be hard to remember and then conjugate.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The use of mnemonics has been proven to help students better learn foreign languages, and this holds true for Spanish verbs.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] A particularly hard verb tense to remember is command verbs.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Command verbs in Spanish are conjugated differently depending on who the command is being given to.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The phrase, when pronounced with a Spanish accent, is used to remember "Ven Di Sal Haz Ten Ve Pon Sé", all of the irregular Spanish command verbs in the you (*tú*) form.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] This mnemonic helps students attempting to memorize different verb tenses.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Another technique is for learners of gendered languages to associate their mental images of words with a colour that matches the gender in the target language.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] An example here is to remember the Spanish word for "foot", *pie**,* [pee-eh] with the image of a foot stepping on a pie, which then spills blue filling (blue representing the male gender of the noun in this example).
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] For French verbs which use être as an auxiliary verb for compound tenses: DR and MRS VANDERTRAMPP: descendre, rester, monter, revenir, sortir, venir, arriver, naître, devenir, entrer, rentrer, tomber, retourner, aller, mourir, partir, passer.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Masculine countries in French (le): "Neither can a breeze make a sane Japanese chilly in the USA." (les) Netherlands (Pays-Bas), Canada, Brazil (Brésil), Mexico (Mexique), Senegal, Japan (Japon), Chile (Chili), & (les) USA (États-Unis d'Amérique).
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Mnemonics can be used in aiding patients with memory deficits that could be caused by head injuries, strokes, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis and other neurological conditions.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] In a study conducted by Doornhein and De Haan, the patients were treated with six different memory strategies including the mnemonics technique.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The results concluded that there were significant improvements on the immediate and delayed subtest of the RBMT, delayed recall on the Appointments test, and relatives rating on the MAC from the patients that received mnemonics treatment.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] However, in the case of stroke patients, the results did not reach statistical significance.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Academic study of the use of mnemonics has shown their effectiveness.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] In one such experiment, subjects of different ages who applied mnemonic techniques to learn novel vocabulary outperformed control groups that applied contextual learning and free-learning styles.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Mnemonics were seen to be more effective for groups of people who struggled with or had weak long-term memory, like the elderly.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Five years after a mnemonic training study, a research team followed-up 112 community-dwelling older adults, 60 years of age and over.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Delayed recall of a word list was assessed prior to, and immediately following mnemonic training, and at the 5-year follow-up.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Overall, there was no significant difference between word recall prior to training and that exhibited at follow-up.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] However, pre-training performance gains scores in performance immediately post-training and use of the mnemonic predicted performance at follow-up.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Individuals who self-reported using the mnemonic exhibited the highest performance overall, with scores significantly higher than at pre-training.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The findings suggest that mnemonic training has long-term benefits for some older adults, particularly those who continue to employ the mnemonic.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] This contrasts with a study from surveys of medical students that approximately only 20% frequently used mnemonic acronyms.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] In humans, the process of aging particularly affects the medial temporal lobe and hippocampus, in which the episodic memory is synthesized.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The episodic memory stores information about items, objects, or features with spatiotemporal contexts.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Since mnemonics aid better in remembering spatial or physical information rather than more abstract forms, its effect may vary according to a subject's age and how well the subject's medial temporal lobe and hippocampus function.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] This could be further explained by one recent study which indicates a general deficit in the memory for spatial locations in aged adults (mean age 69.7 with standard deviation of 7.4 years) compared to young adults (mean age 21.7 with standard deviation of 4.2 years).
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] At first, the difference in target recognition was not significant.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] The researchers then divided the aged adults into two groups, aged unimpaired and aged impaired, according to a neuropsychological testing.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] With the aged groups split, there was an apparent deficit in target recognition in aged impaired adults compared to both young adults and aged unimpaired adults.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] This further supports the varying effectiveness of mnemonics in different age groups.
[src:crypto-wallets/mnemonic] Moreover, different research was done previously with the same notion, which presented with similar results to that of Reagh et al. in a verbal mnemonics discrimination task.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Public key algorithms are fundamental security primitives in modern cryptosystems, including applications and protocols that offer assurance of the confidentiality and authenticity of electronic communications and data storage.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] They underpin numerous Internet standards, such as Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSH, S/MIME, and PGP.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Compared to symmetric cryptography, public-key cryptography can be too slow for many purposes, so these protocols often combine symmetric cryptography with public-key cryptography in hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Before the mid-1970s, all cipher systems used symmetric key algorithms, in which the same cryptographic key is used with the underlying algorithm by both the sender and the recipient, who must both keep the key secret.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Of necessity, the key in every such system had to be exchanged between the communicating parties in some secure way prior to any use of the system – for instance, via a secure channel.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] This requirement is never trivial and very rapidly becomes unmanageable as the number of participants increases, when secure channels are not available, or when (as is sensible cryptographic practice) keys are frequently changed.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] In particular, if messages are meant to be secure from other users, a separate key is required for each possible pair of users.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] By contrast, in a public-key cryptosystem, the public keys can be disseminated widely and openly, and only the corresponding private keys need be kept secret.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] For example, a software publisher can create a signature key pair and include the public key in software installed on computers.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Later, the publisher can distribute an update to the software signed using the private key, and any computer receiving an update can confirm it is genuine by verifying the signature using the public key.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] As long as the software publisher keeps the private key secret, even if a forger can distribute malicious updates to computers, they cannot convince the computers that any malicious updates are genuine.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] For example, a journalist can publish the public key of an encryption key pair on a website so that sources can send secret messages to the news organization in ciphertext.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Only the journalist who knows the corresponding private key can decrypt the ciphertexts to obtain the sources' messages—an eavesdropper reading email on its way to the journalist cannot decrypt the ciphertexts.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] However, public-key encryption does not conceal metadata like what computer a source used to send a message, when they sent it, or how long it is.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Public-key encryption on its own also does not tell the recipient anything about who sent a message—it just conceals the content of the message.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Applications built on public-key cryptography include authenticating web servers with TLS, digital cash, password-authenticated key agreement, authenticating and concealing email content with OpenPGP or S/MIME, and time-stamping services and non-repudiation protocols.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] One important issue is confidence or proof that a particular public key is authentic, i.e., that it is correct and belongs to the person or entity claimed, and has not been tampered with or replaced by some (perhaps malicious) third party.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] A public key infrastructure (PKI), in which one or more third parties, known as certificate authorities, certify ownership of key pairs.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] This implies that the PKI system (software, hardware, and management) can be trusted by all involved.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] A web of trust decentralizes authentication by using individual endorsements of links between a user and their public key.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] PGP uses this approach, in addition to lookup in the domain name system (DNS).
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] The DKIM system for digitally signing emails also uses this approach.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] PGP, SSH, and the SSL/TLS family of schemes use this procedure; they are thus called hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] As with all security-related systems, there are various potential weaknesses in public-key cryptography.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Aside from poor choice of an asymmetric key algorithm (there are few that are widely regarded as satisfactory) or too short a key length, the chief security risk is that the private key of a pair becomes known.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] All security of messages, authentication, etc., encrypted with this private key will then be lost.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] This is commonly mitigated (such as in recent TLS schemes) by using Forward secrecy capable schemes that generate an ephemeral set of keys during the communication which must also be known for the communication to be compromised.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Additionally, with the advent of quantum computing, many asymmetric key algorithms are considered vulnerable to attacks, and new quantum-resistant schemes are being developed to overcome the problem.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Beyond algorithmic or key-length weaknesses, some studies have noted risks when private key control is delegated to third parties.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Research on Uruguay’s implementation of Public Key Infrastructure under Law 18.600 found that centralized key custody by Trust Service Providers (TSPs) may weaken the principle of private-key secrecy, increasing exposure to man-in-the-middle attacks and raising concerns about legal non-repudiation.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] All public key schemes are in theory susceptible to a "brute-force key search attack".
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] However, such an attack is impractical if the amount of computation needed to succeed – termed the "work factor" by Claude Shannon – is out of reach of all potential attackers.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] In many cases, the work factor can be increased by simply choosing a longer key.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] But other algorithms may inherently have much lower work factors, making resistance to a brute-force attack (e.g., from longer keys) irrelevant.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Some special and specific algorithms have been developed to aid in attacking some public key encryption algorithms; both RSA and ElGamal encryption have known attacks that are much faster than the brute-force approach.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] None of these are sufficiently improved to be actually practical, however.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Major weaknesses have been found for several formerly promising asymmetric key algorithms.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] The "knapsack packing" algorithm was found to be insecure after the development of a new attack.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] As with all cryptographic functions, public-key implementations may be vulnerable to side-channel attacks that exploit information leakage to simplify the search for a secret key.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] These are often independent of the algorithm being used.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Research is underway to both discover, and to protect against, new attacks.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Another potential security vulnerability in using asymmetric keys is the possibility of a "man-in-the-middle" attack, in which the communication of public keys is intercepted by a third party (the "man in the middle") and then modified to provide different public keys instead.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Encrypted messages and responses must, in all instances, be intercepted, decrypted, and re-encrypted by the attacker using the correct public keys for the different communication segments so as to avoid suspicion.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] A communication is said to be insecure where data is transmitted in a manner that allows for interception (also called "sniffing").
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] These terms refer to reading the sender's private data in its entirety.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] A communication is particularly unsafe when interceptions can not be prevented or monitored by the sender.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] A man-in-the-middle attack can be difficult to implement due to the complexities of modern security protocols.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] However, the task becomes simpler when a sender is using insecure media such as public networks, the Internet, or wireless communication.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] In these cases an attacker can compromise the communications infrastructure rather than the data itself.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] A hypothetical malicious staff member at an Internet service provider (ISP) might find a man-in-the-middle attack relatively straightforward.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Capturing the public key would only require searching for the key as it gets sent through the ISP's communications hardware; in properly implemented asymmetric key schemes, this is not a significant risk.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] In some advanced man-in-the-middle attacks, one side of the communication will see the original data while the other will receive a malicious variant.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Asymmetric man-in-the-middle attacks can prevent users from realizing their connection is compromised.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] This remains so even when one user's data is known to be compromised because the data appears fine to the other user.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] This can lead to confusing disagreements between users such as "it must be on your end!" when neither user is at fault.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Hence, man-in-the-middle attacks are only fully preventable when the communications infrastructure is physically controlled by one or both parties; such as via a wired route inside the sender's own building.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] In summation, public keys are easier to alter when the communications hardware used by a sender is controlled by an attacker.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] One approach to prevent such attacks involves the use of a public key infrastructure (PKI); a set of roles, policies, and procedures needed to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key encryption.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Web browsers, for instance, are supplied with a long list of "self-signed identity certificates" from PKI providers – these are used to check the *bona fides* of the certificate authority and then, in a second step, the certificates of potential communicators.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who could subvert one of those certificate authorities into issuing a certificate for a bogus public key could then mount a "man-in-the-middle" attack as easily as if the certificate scheme were not used at all.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who penetrates an authority's servers and obtains its store of certificates and keys (public and private) would be able to spoof, masquerade, decrypt, and forge transactions without limit, assuming that they were able to place themselves in the communication stream.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Despite its theoretical and potential problems, Public key infrastructure is widely used.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Examples include TLS and its predecessor SSL, which are commonly used to provide security for web browser transactions (for example, most websites utilize TLS for HTTPS).
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Aside from the resistance to attack of a particular key pair, the security of the certification hierarchy must be considered when deploying public key systems.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Some certificate authority – usually a purpose-built program running on a server computer – vouches for the identities assigned to specific private keys by producing a digital certificate.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Public key digital certificates are typically valid for several years at a time, so the associated private keys must be held securely over that time.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] When a private key used for certificate creation higher in the PKI server hierarchy is compromised, or accidentally disclosed, then a "man-in-the-middle attack" is possible, making any subordinate certificate wholly insecure.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Most of the available public-key encryption software does not conceal metadata in the message header, which might include the identities of the sender and recipient, the sending date, subject field, and the software they use etc.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Rather, only the body of the message is concealed and can only be decrypted with the private key of the intended recipient.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] This means that a third party could construct quite a detailed model of participants in a communication network, along with the subjects being discussed, even if the message body itself is hidden.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] However, there has been a recent demonstration of messaging with encrypted headers, which obscures the identities of the sender and recipient, and significantly reduces the available metadata to a third party.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] The concept is based around an open repository containing separately encrypted metadata blocks and encrypted messages.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Only the intended recipient is able to decrypt the metadata block, and having done so they can identify and download their messages and decrypt them.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Such a messaging system is at present in an experimental phase and not yet deployed.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Scaling this method would reveal to the third party only the inbox server being used by the recipient and the timestamp of sending and receiving.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] The server could be shared by thousands of users, making social network modelling much more challenging.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] During the early history of cryptography, two parties would rely upon a key that they would exchange by means of a secure, but non-cryptographic, method such as a face-to-face meeting, or a trusted courier.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] This key, which both parties must then keep absolutely secret, could then be used to exchange encrypted messages.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] A number of significant practical difficulties arise with this approach to distributing keys.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Here he described the relationship of one-way functions to cryptography, and went on to discuss specifically the factorization problem used to create a trapdoor function.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Ellis, a British cryptographer at the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), conceived of the possibility of "non-secret encryption", (now called public key cryptography), but could see no way to implement it.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] In 1973, his colleague Clifford Cocks implemented what has become known as the RSA encryption algorithm, giving a practical method of "non-secret encryption", and in 1974 another GCHQ mathematician and cryptographer, Malcolm J.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Williamson, developed what is now known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] The scheme was also passed to the US's National Security Agency.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Both organisations had a military focus and only limited computing power was available in any case; the potential of public key cryptography remained unrealised by either organization.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] These discoveries were not publicly acknowledged until the research was declassified by the British government in 1997.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] In 1976, an asymmetric key cryptosystem was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman who, influenced by Ralph Merkle's work on public key distribution, disclosed a method of public key agreement.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] This method of key exchange, which uses exponentiation in a finite field, came to be known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] This was the first published practical method for establishing a shared secret-key over an authenticated (but not confidential) communications channel without using a prior shared secret.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Merkle's "public key-agreement technique" became known as Merkle's Puzzles, and was invented in 1974 and only published in 1978.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] This makes asymmetric encryption a rather new field in cryptography although cryptography itself dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] In 1977, a generalization of Cocks's scheme was independently invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, all then at MIT.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] The latter authors published their work in 1978 in Martin Gardner's Scientific American column, and the algorithm came to be known as RSA, from their initials.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] RSA uses exponentiation modulo a product of two very large primes, to encrypt and decrypt, performing both public key encryption and public key digital signatures.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Its security is connected to the extreme difficulty of factoring large integers, a problem for which there is no known efficient general technique.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] A description of the algorithm was published in the Mathematical Games column in the August 1977 issue of Scientific American.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] Since the 1970s, a large number and variety of encryption, digital signature, key agreement, and other techniques have been developed, including the Rabin signature, ElGamal encryption, DSA and ECC.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] In addition to the algorithms developed within the open academic and standards communities, several countries have developed national public-key cryptography standards for use within their jurisdictions.
[src:crypto-wallets/public-key-cryptography] These include SM2 and SM9 (China), GOST R 34.10-2012 (Russia), EC-KCDSA (South Korea), and DSTU 4145 (Ukraine).
